Sync vs Async Operations in Node.js
1. Synchronous (Sync) Operation

Synchronous execution means:

Code runs step by step
Next line executes only after the previous one finishes
It is blocking in nature
Example (Sync)
const fs = require('fs');

console.log("Start");

const data = fs.readFileSync('input.txt', 'utf8');
console.log(data);

console.log("End");
Output Flow
Start
(file content)
End

The program waits until the file is completely read.

Key Points
Blocking execution
Slower for large operations
Easier to understand
2. Asynchronous (Async) Operation

Asynchronous execution means:

Tasks run in the background
Code continues executing without waiting
It is non-blocking
Example (Async)
const fs = require('fs');

console.log("Start");

fs.readFile('input.txt', 'utf8', (err, data) => {
    console.log(data);
});

console.log("End");
Output Flow
Start
End
(file content)

The file is read after the main code continues.

Key Points
Non-blocking execution
Faster for real-world applications
Used in backend systems
3. Example using setTimeout
console.log("Start");

setTimeout(() => {
    console.log("Task done");
}, 2000);

console.log("End");
Output
Start
End
Task done
4. Difference Between Sync and Async
Feature	Sync	Async
Execution	Blocking	Non-blocking
Speed	Slower	Faster
Use Case	Small tasks	Real applications
Example	readFileSync	readFile
5. Node.js Internals

Node.js is single-threaded but efficient because of:

Event Loop
Callbacks
Non-blocking I/O
6. When to Use
Use Sync when:
Writing small scripts
Debugging
Simple operations
Use Async when:
Building APIs
Handling files
Working with databases
Developing backend systems
7. Modern Approach (Async/Await)
const fs = require('fs').promises;

async function run() {
    console.log("Start");

    const data = await fs.readFile('input.txt', 'utf8');
    console.log(data);

    console.log("End");
}

run();
8. Important Concepts
Callback: Function passed as an argument
Promise: Handles async results
Async/Await: Cleaner syntax for async code
9. Interview Definition

Synchronous operations block execution until completion, while asynchronous operations allow non-blocking execution using callbacks, promises, or async/await.

Final Summary
Sync means wait for each step
Async means continue execution without waiting
Node.js uses async behavior to achieve high performance
